                <pb/> 
                    <p>Monday, February 6, 1922</p>
                    <p>
                        Exercise: Combination of rigid and fluid (or loose) 
                        rhythms. The end result should be the composition. The 
                        tasks from earlier exercises can be incorporated.
                        E.g., applying a rigid rhythm to the individuum, a loose
                        rhythm to the structural;
                        or, applying a [loose] rhythm to the individuum, [rigid] 
                        to the structural; 
                        or, two individuums affecting each other mutually, one 
                        loose and the other rigid.
                    </p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="div_Klee_lesson6">
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../number6"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        Monday, February 13, 1922
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        I am beginning today with criticism of an imperfect 
                        solution to the last exercise, but by no means wish 
                        to imply that there were fewer good solutions than 
                        previously. I am likewise reluctant to reprove the 
                        author of the imperfect solution; rather, I would 
                        like to use his error as an opportunity for remarks 
                        from which we may all learn and benefit.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The exercise was based upon the previous theoretical 
                        remarks about rigid and loose articulation. It was 
                        called, "Combination of rigidly articulated characters 
                        with loosely articulated characters into an organic 
                        whole (the composition)." 
                    </p>
                    <p> In this regard, I made several suggestions:</p>
                    <p>
                        1)  to treat the rigid articulation individually and 
                        to subordinate the loose articulation in support 
                        of the individuum. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Or, 2)  to dedicate the loose articulation to the 
                        individuum, and (conversely) to keep the rigid 
                        articulation structural.
                    </p>
                <pb/>
                    <p>
                       In music, both ways of treating two characters are 
                        described as melodic (solo voice with accompaniment).
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                        Thirdly, I suggested letting both kinds of articu
                        lation struggle for equivalence, which in music is 
                        called thematic treatment.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Or, fourth, treating both types of articulation 
                        as having the same power, so that they would not 
                        struggle against each other but rather, amicably 
                        complementing each other, they would mutually and 
                        alternately grant the upper hand. Once again, an 
                        example of thematic treatment.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Now, a spirited colleague of yours chose 
                        quite simple forms and established a rhythm with 
                        dynamic light and dark accentuation, on the one hand, 
                        with straight lines:
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig1"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>and, on the other, with circles:</p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig2"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        So, are both these characters suitable 
                        examples of rigid and fluid articulation?
                    </p>
                    <p> 
                        To begin with the first character,
                        What is this?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig3"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        It is a plane that approaches the  
                        linear in an upright direction,
                        like this <graphic url="..."/> or <graphic url="..."/> this.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        And what is 
                        this?
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig4"/>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        It is a rigidly articulated expansion and contraction of 
                        a row of planes that approach linearity.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The expansion and contraction develops in a hori- 
                        zontal direction, like this <graphic url="..."/> or this <graphic url="..."/>. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The sense of which can also be represented in the 
                        following manner:
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig5"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        The first character (fig. 1) therefore conforms to the 
                        exercise. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        But what about the second character? Does the row of 
                        swelling and shrinking circles correspond to the task? 
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig6"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Yes, since the articulation around a common point cannot 
                        be described as rigid, much less when fig. 6 allows for 
                        other interpretations, such as in fig. 7,
                    </p> 
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig7"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p> or in fig. 8,</p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig8"/>
                    </figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>or their variants, 7a and 8a.</p> 
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig7a"/>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig8a"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        So the row of circles as a loosely articulated 
                        character also corresponds quite closely to the 
                        proposed task. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Now, how did both characters behave in relation 
                        to one another in the solution I objected to? 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If, on the one hand, we had an individuum and, 
                        on the other, a structural character, then we could 
                        resort to guessing and try our luck. But here both 
                        characters are developed equally little. I remember 
                        that they behaved like this, 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="center"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig9"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        in relation to 
                        each other.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/> Or, actually, like this:
                        <cb n="center"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig10"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>And that means?
                    </p>
                <pb/>
                    <p> Alas, nothing in the sense of the proposed task.</p>
                    <p>
                        In itself, it could well mean something, namely, 
                        either a bipartite or tripartite unit, perhaps an 
                        everyday object like a lamp with a base, globe, and 
                        cylinder,
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url="..."/>
                        <cb n="center"/><graphic url="..."/>
                    </p>
                    <p>or a pot-bellied vase,<graphic url="..."/></p>
                    <p> or a clock pendulum,<graphic url="..."/> or any object at all: <graphic url="..."/></p>
                    <p>
                        However, the requirement, a "Composition based on 
                        two characters" no doubt permits manifold solutions, 
                        except that their fusion into a single thing is not 
                        possible,
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        because <graphic url="..."/> or <graphic url="..."/> is no organic confrontation
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        between <graphic url="..."/> circle and <graphic url="..."/> straight line!
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Nor is the repetition of this motif a solution to 
                        the question!
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig12"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        So that we may more easily assess this motif by translating 
                        it into a material case, with this construct (fig. 12), for 
                        example, we can imagine a row of pieces of wood of unequal 
                        weight, shaped like piano keys,
                        <graphic url="..."/> upon which the tops
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        of tin cans have
                        been placed:
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig13"/>
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                        In this case, there are no longer unified objects 
                        but rather two material characters without a visible 
                        relationship, merely superimposed, completely 
                        lacking spirit.
                    </p>
                    <p>In short: the</p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig14"/>
                        <figDesc>
                        relation less ness 
                        of two heterogeneous
                        things:  
                        </figDesc>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Thus, once again nothing! But what can one do 
                        so that it becomes something?  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        So as to continue imagining this in material 
                        terms, let us first of all leave the row of wooden 
                        pieces of different weights at rest where they are, 
                        but instead of the circular planes made of tin, 
                        atop the wooden pieces we will place a bull's-eye 
                        of crown glass or optical lenses or glass spheres.
                        And,  visibly, something will occur, 
                        namely, the pic- <graphic url="..."/> -torial expression of 
                        the relationship between two hetero-
                        geneous things.
                        (See figs. 15, 16, 17.)
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <figure>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig15"/>
                        <cb n="center"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig16"/>
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig17"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        What kind of relationship between the two characters do 
                        we now behold?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The struggle of the aggressive straight line against 
                        the inherently quiescent circle, and the defeat of the 
                        straight line when it falls within the dangerous region 
                        of its partner. Struggle at the expense of the straight 
                        line. Victory of the fluid character over the rigid.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The following example teaches us another way 
                        pictorially to express the relationship between two 
                        heterogeneous things (fig. 18 and following):
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig18"/>
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig19"/>
                    </figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        The straight line applies sharpness of the most aggres-
                        sive sort, it becomes an arrow shot off, and it carries 
                        out its struggle at the expense of the circle. The 
                        circle has visibly succumbed (figs. 18 and 19).
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig20"/>
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig21"/>
                        <figDesc>
                        (20/21) The circle is defeated once again. 
                        </figDesc>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Leaving aside the various types of struggle, I shall 
                        proceed to the question of adaptation.  
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig22"/>
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig23"/>
                        <figDesc>
                            (22/23) Struggle is avoided by the     adaptive evasion
                        </figDesc>
                    </figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        of the straight line, which in the first case takes 
                        place along one side and in the other by splitting.  
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig24"/>
                        <figDesc>
                           (24)  Struggle is avoided by the circle adaptively 
                            shaping itself snugly, becoming an ellipse. 
                        </figDesc>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig25"/>
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig26"/>
                        <figDesc>
                            (25/26) And here, finally, we have examples of   
                            both characters' reciprocal adaptation. Each, 
                            encountering its partner, obligingly adopts
                        </figDesc>
                    </figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        a modified shape. The circle is no longer a circle, 
                        the straight line no longer a straight line.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Further examples would not contribute anything 
                        essentially new, so I shall limit myself to these 
                        few. Depending on the spirit of the emerging 
                        composition, I shall choose one of these typical 
                        motifs or the other and will have a configuration 
                        of struggle or of friendship. The struggle can be 
                        carried out with varying sharpness; friendship can 
                        be based on unilateral or mutual adaptation.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The interpretation of the constructive process 
                        can be even richer in relationships if I designate 
                        the straight line as masculine, on account of 
                        its spontaneous activity, and if, conversely, I 
                        designate the circle as feminine in its inherent 
                        quiescence.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig12"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Now, in our example that provided the occasion for 
                        this criticism, however, the motifs we have just 
                        discussed in terms of the extended compositional 
                        configuration were handled in a manner so unrelated 
                        that one could say,
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        "The men are monks, the women are nuns, and, despite 
                        the close proximity of the two cloisters, no life 
                        can arise in this pictorial representation."
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        My previous discussions of the structural concept 
                        dealt with the most primitive structural type based on 
                        repeating rhythms.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In the practical exercises, however, a structural 
                        element often appeared that rose above this primitivity. 
                        I found no reason to object to a structural element 
                        of this kind as long as a higher development stood 
                        against it or rested above it, qua individuum.   
                    </p>
                    <p>Relativity here as everywhere, I told myself.</p>
                    <p>
                        The science of anatomy teaches us, usually by way 
                        of introduction, to recognize in their structure the 
                        matter from which plants or animals are constructed. 
                        A knife is used for this purpose. This science 
                        understands structure as the grouping of the smallest 
                        corpuscles of matter that are visible with the naked 
                        eye or a microscope.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Matter that, for example, has undergone the ravages 
                        of erosion offers similar structural images.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In any case, one can perhaps even detect with the 
                        naked eye the rhythm of the corpuscles in a bone, the 
                        result of which is a multitude of cavities akin to 
                        cells* or tubes or channels.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig27"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                       <note> * As examples, a weathered cabbage stalk and a piece of bone.</note> 
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        In a similar fashion, one can detect the structure 
                        of cartilage, ligaments, tendons, and muscles, etc.
                    </p> 
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig28"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        The structure of ligaments is (fig. 28) a sinewy web 
                        of fiber. 
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig29"/>
                        <figDesc>
                            (29) The fibers of the  
                            tendons merge into  
                            muscle fibers, in which a second, crosswise-striped 
                            structure ensues.
                        </figDesc>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Enough, then, about the material structure and 
                        about the rhythm of the material that the organs 
                        and the organism are made of. Let us now visualize 
                        the organism as a movement-machine, in which the 
                        execution of the movement and the will to move 
                        interlock, and let us build up from subservient 
                        elements to governing elements. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Here let matter be a precondition in the entire 
                        domain of action; it should be everywhere.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Now, if we first consider the bones' relation- 
                        ship to one another, interacting to make the 
                        skeleton, then we recognize straightaway that even 
                        in a resting position they need to be held
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>together. The ligaments see to this.</p> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig30"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        The ligaments connect 
                        several bones, they 
                        serve the bones, their 
                        function is subordinate, 
                        they provide support 
                        by connecting, they are 
                        subordinated.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Their function, as such, has a structural character 
                        in relation to the bones' higher task of movement.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Therefore, in arranging the 
                        schema of action, I will allow the  
                        ligament only a little space, but 
                        somewhat more space for the bone:
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig31"/>
                    </figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        If I consider the relationship of bone to muscle 
                        with regard to the movement-organism, 
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig32"/>
                        B bone
                        T tendon
                        M muscle
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        then I recognize that 
                        here the tendon carries 
                        out a similar mediating 
                        function as did the 
                        ligament previously, 
                        in the way in which the 
                        tendon joins the muscle 
                        to the bone (fig. 32).
                    </p>
                    <p>And how does the muscle relate to the bone?</p>
                    <figure>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig33"/>
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url=".../lesson6_fig33a"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        It can force the bone into a new position, since 
                        the muscle has the ability to contract and, in the 
                        process, to shorten itself. And, at the same time, 
                        tendons and ligaments help by tenaciously holding 
                        tight. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The angle between two bones must change because the 
                        muscle wills it. The muscle's function of movement
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        is therefore of a higher order than the bones' 
                        function of movement. The passivity of the bone 
                        depends on the activity of the muscle. The function 
                        of the bone is functional-structural in relation 
                        to the function of the muscle. It helps the muscle 
                        translate the movement-command (wherever it comes 
                        from) into action.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Therefore, in my schema of the action of 
                        movement, I allow a larger space for the muscle, 
                        and leave the tendon to mediate between them.  
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig34"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        The muscles perform mutually independent functions.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Each muscle has a specific task; one bends the 
                        organ, the other stretches it, etc. Here, too, we 
                        observe functioning of a higher order than that of 
                        the bone, which can achieve nothing by itself but 
                        only in conjunction with a second bone. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        But since we have already mentioned the word 
                        "movement-command," the muscle's active self-mastery 
                        extends only so far. It obeys as soon as the command 
                        reaches it; it does not want to act but must act; at 
                        most it wants to obey.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        It obeys the brain's command, transmitted 
                        telegraphically by the nerve cord.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Our schema of the action of movement is again 
                        expanded:  
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig35"/>
                    </figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        What do we learn (from fig. 35)? We recognize, first  
                        of all, the relativity of serving and governing, of 
                        structural and individual functioning: as a whole, a 
                        nested structure (a box in a box in a box).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The progression of the functional values goes 
                        according to spatial or quantitative points of view: 
                        "That which is greater requires more room." The direc- 
                        tion is eccentric. Higher values withdraw further 
                        and further from the central point; the significance 
                        increases as we go from the center away towards the 
                        periphery.  
                    </p> 
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig36"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        The notional passageway whose point of origin is 
                        the brain--and which confers a central significance 
                        and quality on this organ and allows it to transmit 
                        commands in every direction--would lead us to an 
                        inverse, concentric representation, or a qualitative 
                        representation.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        By means of the nerves, the brain subjects the
                    </p>
                <pb/>
                    <p>
                        muscles to its will, and through the muscles the 
                        command, by means of the tendons, reaches the 
                        bones, until, despite being earth-bound, the whole 
                        material mass nevertheless indeed moves. 
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson6_fig37"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        Exercise for February 20, 1922
                        Task: Tripartite organism:
                        I. organ: active (brain)      
                        II.  "    medial (muscle)
                        III. "    passive (bone)
                        or weight criterion:
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        <graphic url="..."/>
                        length criterion 
                        in lieu of weight 
                        criterion 
                    </p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="div_Klee_lesson7">
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../number7"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        Monday, February 27, 1922
                    </p>
                    <p> The exercise from the last meeting was:</p>
                    <p>
                        Tripartite organism;
                        First organ, active character (brain)
                        Second organ, medial character (muscle)
                        Third organ, passive character (bone)
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Brain, muscle and bone were not to be represented 
                        as such but rather were to be understood schematically, 
                        in view of their position within the animal movement
                        organism that I had discussed.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The concepts of active, medial, and passive can be 
                        best explained in philological or linguistic terms:
                        If I say, "I impel," it is an active form.
                        If I say, "I am impelled," it is the linguistic expres- 
                        sion of the passive.
                        But the expression of the medial form would be: 
                        I integrate myself, I fit myself in, 
                        I make friends of myself. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        It is also worth noting that the ancient languages 
                        of the civilized nations could form the passive voice 
                        without an auxiliary verb, purely morphologically, 
                        by means of a particular verb ending. I still even 
                        remember the pure medial form in Greek, expressed 
                        only in the verb ending, with no pronoun whatsoever. 
                        The modern languages no longer convey these three 
                        characters by means of purely synthetic verbal forms, 
                        using for this purpose instead several roundabout 
                        combinations of words.  
                    </p>
                    <p>As for the rank of these three characters, active,</p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        medial, and passive, it will depend on different 
                        points of view.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Conceptually, the active would be classified as 
                        principal, because the impulse to move starts in the 
                        brain, because in it resides thought, the father of 
                        all more highly developed action.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        From the material point of view, the order would 
                        be the inverse, and we would say that the rigid 
                        matter, the bone, first realizes the movement and 
                        that it belongs in first place. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        It is not necessary to set the two points of view 
                        against each other. What is essential is the organically 
                        shared unity of the three as left, center, and right 
                        organs or as right, center, and left organs.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Considering the particular difficulty of the 
                        exercise I counted myself satisfied with solutions 
                        whose organic coherence was plainly evident,
                        on the one hand, in the form of the organs
                        themselves,
                        on the other, in the emphasis given in this form's
                        representation.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        First example: the water mill <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig1"/>
                        principal organ: the water 
                        other organs:  two wheels,one large and one 
                        small, connected by a drive-belt.
                        Criticism:  a) Formal error in the choice of 
                        the lower organs, because in the 
                        relationship of significance to 
                        the principal organ, there is 
                        no stepwise organic tripartite 
                        division.
                        b) Formal error in the shape of 
                        the main organ; its form is at best a
                    </p>
                <pb/>
                    <p>
                        conventional undulating structure just the way you 
                        "do water," but not an outstanding configuration of 
                        a main organ.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        c) Error of emphasis: the principal organ, water, 
                        is treated too lightly in dynamic terms.   
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <figDesc> 
                            Correction: (fig. 2)
                        </figDesc>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig2"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        a) Relationally correct choice of organs: I. The 
                        waterfall, active, brain; II. The coupled wheels, 
                        medial, muscle; III. The hammer, passive, bone.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        b) Relationally correct formation of organs: The 
                        principal organ is articulated with the greatest 
                        individuality; the others are articulated decreasingly 
                        so, by steps.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        c) Relationally correct emphasis of organs: I. with 
                        principal energy, II. with medium energy, III. with 
                        negligible energy.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig3"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        As a result, as far as configuration and emphasis are 
                        concerned, the erroneousness of fig. 3 in relational 
                        terms should be readily apparent. The most improbable
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        scenario arises: the medial organ has become the 
                        principal organ.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        (Example one A):
                        With the choice of organs, I can expand 
                        the failed example (fig. 1) upwards as well, instead 
                        of downwards (as was the case when the hammer 
                        was added). So we remove the hammer, the wheel 
                        becomes III, the water becomes II, and I shall 
                        think of something new for I. This proves easier, 
                        since flowing water does not yet correspond to any 
                        originating initiative.   
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                        We are familiar with the earth's force of gravity 
                        (fig. 4),
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig4"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        just as we are familiar with the horizontal 
                        corresponding to the level of "standing" water:   
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig5"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Without the mountains A and B hemming it in, the water 
                        would drain off on both sides:
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig6"/>
                    </figure>
                <pb/>
                    <p>
                        If we remove mountain B and leave mountain A standing, 
                        then the water only flows off to the right. As a 
                        result, two forces are at work, first gravity, second 
                        the obstructing mountain (fig. 7). 
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig7"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        These two forces result in the diagonal of the 
                        parallelogram of forces: II, the force of the flowing 
                        water.   
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson7_fig8"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        In linguistic terms:
                        I: "We impel." (active)
                        II: "I resign myself," 
                        but I is held respon- 
                        sible, lest anyone  
                        further down suffer  
                        (medial).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson7_fig9"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        And someone does  
                        suffer it:
                        III: the wheel, which  
                        says,
                        "I am turned" (passive). 
                        (fig. 9) 
                    </p>
                <pb/>
                    <p>
                        Erroneous emphasis in this variant of the example 
                        looks like this:
                    </p> 
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig10"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Another example:  I: Let the active force be the 
                        soil in which the seed sprouts;
                        let the relational complex (humus/seed/
                        nourishment/growth/taking root) 
                        produce the form I (fig. 11)  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson7_fig11"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        II: Having emerged into 
                        the light and in 
                        the open air, the 
                        respiratory organs 
                        form: one or two 
                        leaves, 
                        and more leaves,
                        and more leaves.
                        III: As a result, the 
                        flower, at which 
                        point the plant is 
                        fully grown.
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_11a"/>
                        The wrong emphasis.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Variant for another example: With the function of the 
                        flower, the sexual phase begins, which 
                        serves the purposes of reproduction.
                        Here, in that case, one could perhaps 
                        claim the following as characteristic 
                        for our tripartite order:
                        as I: stamen and pollen,
                        as II: the mediation of insects,
                        as III: the fertilized seeds. 
                    </p>
                    <p>Third example: circulation</p>
                    <p>
                       We could broaden our studies of nature in the field 
                        of anatomy yet further, from the realm of voluntary 
                        movement to that of involuntary movement. 
                    </p> 
                    <p></p>
                    <p> 
                        Voluntary movement occurs, as the expression 
                        indicates, following a command, according to the 
                        requirements of the authority we commonly call the 
                        brain. It hardly ever applies to the entire movement 
                        apparatus, but rather sets merely partial couplings 
                        into action. This part of the animal movement-machine 
                        is subject to fatigue; the norm here is fatigue, 
                        sluggishness, and, when called for, suspension (in 
                        sleep).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The involuntary movements of the other part of the 
                        machine: of the heart, of the lungs, of the digestive 
                        and excretive systems. These involuntary movements do 
                        not cease during a lifetime. Here fatigue, sluggishness, 
                        and missing a beat are not allowed for.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig12"/>
                        <figDesc>
                            I: heart
                            II: lung
                            III: blood of 
                            arteries and veins
                        </figDesc>
                    </figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                    I: The heart pumps (active).)
                    III:  The blood flows through the arteries; 
                    it is moved (passive).
                    II: The lungs purify; they take part in purifying 
                    (medial).
                    III:  The blood flows passively back to the 
                    heart again.
                    I: The heart pumps again (active).
                    III:  The blood is set again in motion and returns 
                    to the place of the heart from where the 
                    circulation began (passive).
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                        All this as a postscript to our last exercise... 
                        The schematic concision of my presentation has probably 
                        been evident to you; on the one hand it clarifies 
                        matters plainly while, on the other, it leaves open to 
                        you the most diverse ways of configuring the formal 
                        concepts and relationships we have examined.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Now, in order to configure formal relationships 
                        of this type (made even more specific in our exercise), 
                        namely, movement (in our special case, movement that is 
                        elicited, transmitted, and compelled)--in order to let 
                        the relationships of movement, on the basis of analytic 
                        abstraction, return to their nature, to the work's 
                        own nature--for that purpose, we shall still require 
                        something beyond a clearly thought-out schema.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        What does movement in the work actually mean? As a 
                        rule, after all, our works won't be moving, will they? 
                        We are, after all, not an automaton factory!
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        No, most of our works will, of their own accord, 
                        remain at rest in their place. Yet, nevertheless, they 
                        are wholly movement.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Movement is proper to all becoming, and before the 
                        work is, the work becomes, just like the world. Before 
                        it was--according to the quotation, "in the beginning 
                        God created..."--it became; and furthermore, it becomes 
                        before in the future it is.
                        will be 
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        The work becomes: stone upon stone or, from the 
                        block, piece from piece.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig13"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        That is the initial productive-movement, the 
                        beginning action of the one who is creating. This 
                        beginning action is already of a temporal nature, 
                        whether it remains flat or results in a volume: this 
                        takes time. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Shortly after this initial productive-movement, 
                        the first counter-movement already begins with the 
                        creator: the initial receptive-movement. Or, in 
                        everyday language, he inspects what he has made up to 
                        this point. ("...And he saw that it was good," as it 
                        is written.)
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Once again, a temporal process. Only the tiniest  
                        thing of all--the point, dead unto itself--is timeless.  
                        As soon as this point becomes movement and line, it 
                        requires time, in the same way as when this line is 
                        pushed to produce a plane or when the movement of 
                        planes produces volumes. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        From a cosmic standpoint, movement is actually a 
                        given, and as an infinite force it requires no special 
                        energetic impetus. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The inhibition, by matter, of this given 
                        movement results in the quiescence of things in the 
                        earthly sphere. It is misguided to assume that this 
                        adhesion to the earth is the norm.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The history of the work, which is first and 
                        foremost genesis, can be described briefly in broad 
                        strokes as a hidden spark from somewhere that, 
                        glowing, ignites the human spirit, moves the human 
                        hand and from there is transmitted as movement of 
                        matter; it becomes work.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        The receptive process is equivalent. The beholder (who 
                        can be the same as the creator) goes, so to speak, in the 
                        opposite direction. But the beholder, too, is completely 
                        moved in time.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In just physical terms: The eye does not register 
                        forms on even the simplest plane with simultaneously 
                        equal intensity. It lacks the physical capacity to do so, 
                        because the retina does not perceive the entire image 
                        with the same acuity,
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig14"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        but rather, only the section I adjacent to the point that 
                        can be joined by a straight line with the focal point 
                        of the lens and with the center of visual acuity on the 
                        retina. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If the eye wishes to sharply perceive section II of 
                        the object, then it must turn upwards. If it wishes to 
                        perceive section III sharply, then it must be lowered.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Eye muscles turn the eye here and there--from left to 
                        right, from corner to corner, around in a circle--and 
                        the sections it sees sharply, one after the other, are 
                        gradually registered in the brain to create an overall 
                        impression. The brain has the capacity to store memory 
                        images and to assemble them into a whole; the eye has the 
                        ability to visit a spot over and over again to inspect 
                        and consolidate.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        We know full well that the image in the eye is actually inverted, 
                        but this alters essentially nothing at all in the process.   
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig15"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                       Stage I: The beholder perceives the central section, I. 
                        Sections II and III lack sharpness on the retina. The 
                        muscles for lowering and raising the eye are not involved. 
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig16"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Stage II: The beholder's eye now 
                        obeys the desire to examine the upper 
                        region clearly. The lower muscle
                        muscle for raising contracts
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        becomes active, contracting until it brings the eye into 
                        the new position where the area of acuity on the retina, 
                        the focal point of the lens, and area II of the object 
                        lie in a straight line.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Area I is still perceived but less sharply, while 
                        III, which was previously still perceptible though 
                        without clarity, leaves the field of vision.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig17"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Stage III (fig.17): The eye should obey the beholder's 
                        desire to perceive the lower region in full sharpness. 
                        For this purpose the muscle for lowering the eye is 
                        able to contract, and the eye follows effortlessly, 
                        until the retina's center of visual acuity, the focal 
                        point of the lens, and part III of the object lie in 
                        a straight line. Thus, I remains visible (though not 
                        sharply), while II leaves the field of vision.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In this way the eye, like a grazing animal, scans 
                        a plane not only from bottom to top, but also from 
                        left to right and in every direction, where it has 
                        reason to do so. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        It traverses the paths set out for it in the work, 
                        which itself emerged through movement and became 
                        movement fixed in place.
                    </p> 
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>It traverses these paths in various ways, 
                        according to the work's constitution. If the work has 
                        been constructed with resoluteness and stability,  
                        then the eye goes about its grazing, proceeding from  
                        the values that attract it initially, to those that 
                        attract it later, once the first values have been grazed 
                        over (fig. 18). 
                        <cb n="right"/> 
                        with a succes
                        sive devel- 
                        opment of  
                        values,
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If, from a formal standpoint, the work has been 
                        constructed with resoluteness and stability but at the 
                        same time is governed by markedly contrasting values, 
                        then the eye moves more in leaps and bounds, in the 
                        manner of an animal hunting (fig. 19). 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If the work, however, is not resolute and not stable 
                        as far as the form of its values is concerned, but loose 
                        and itself movement and flow, then the eye abandons itself 
                        to this current like a little boat, or it sails like a 
                        cloud in lightly or stormily moving winds (fig. 20).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson7_fig18"/>
                        <cb n="centre"/><graphic url=".../lesson7_fig19"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        Higher activity  
                        is proper to 
                        dynamic-form 
                        works.
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig20"/>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Now we'll practice what we've learned so far, with some examples.                   </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson7_fig21"/>
                        <cb n="centre"/>
                        First example:  for stable formation.  Statements:
                        Formation: stable <graphic url="..."/> 
                        Arrangement: vertical <graphic url="..."/>
                        Articulation: rigid <graphic url="..."/>
                        Development: progressive increase<graphic url="..."/>
                        Direction of increase:  
                        from top to bottom 
                        <graphic url="..."/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        Conceptual 
                        statement:  
                        the notion  
                        of the  
                        weight of 
                        matter. 
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson7_fig22"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        Function modified in terms of reception: The beholder's 
                        eye immediately 
                        catches the lushest 
                        spot in the pasture, 
                        no. 1; it compares 
                        that with no. 2, 
                        compares that with no. 
                        3, etc. (fig. 22). 
                        Base below.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson7_fig23"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        Second example
                        Formation: stable <graphic url="..."/>
                        Functions: Arrangement: vertical <graphic url="..."/>
                        Articulation: rigid<graphic url="..."/>
                        Development: progressive increase <graphic url="..."/>
                        Direction: from bottom to top <graphic url="..."/>
                        Formal
                        statement
                        Conceptual statement: Overcoming the
                        material force of gravity
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson7_fig24"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        Function modified in terms of reception: The beholder's 
                        eye steers to the place 
                        in the pasture where the 
                        grass grows thickest, 
                        no. 1, compares that 
                        with no. 2, and compares 
                        that with no. 3, no. 4, 
                        and no. 5. Base above.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p> Third example</p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson7_fig25"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        Formal statement: Formation: stable <graphic url="..."/>
                        Functions: Arrangement: vertical <graphic url="..."/>
                        Articulation: rigid <graphic url="..."/>
                        Development:
                        progressive
                        increase and 
                        progressive decrease
                        <graphic url="..."/>
                        Direction of increase:
                        from top to middle 
                        and from bottom to 
                        middle
                        <graphic url="..."/>
                        (Direction of decrease:
                        from the middle 
                        upwards and from
                        the middle down)
                        <graphic url="..."/>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        Conceptual statement:  combination of the 
                        materialistic and the 
                        idealistic conceptions.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="center"/><graphic url="..."/>ideal
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url="..."/>material
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson7_fig26"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        Function modified in terms of reception: The beholder's eye is caught 
                        principally by the 
                        values 1 and 2; it 
                        oscillates between 
                        1 and 2, compares 3 
                        and 5 with 1 and 2, 
                        and, finally, also 
                        compares 4. Base, 
                        middle
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>Fourth example</p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig27"/>
                    </figure> 
                    <p>Formal statement:</p>
                    <p>Formation: stable<graphic url="..."/></p>
                    <p>
                        Functions: Arrangement: diagonal<graphic url="..."/>
                        Articulation: rigid<graphic url="..."/>
                    </p>
                    <p> Development: increase and decrease<graphic url="..."/></p>
                    <p> 
                        Direction of increase: from
                        outside to inside<graphic url="..."/>
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p> Receptive function:</p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson7_fig28"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        The principal weight, 1, catches the beholder's 
                        eye to a marked degree, because this principal 
                        weight is also located at the most important place; 
                        then the eye oscillates back and forth as it circles 
                        around towards the four 2s and then oscillates 
                        around in a new circle towards the four 3s.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        We learn: The movement-function of a work need not 
                        be emphasized as such. For as you have seen, the most 
                        quiescent and stable work is also movement.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Nevertheless, the question as to the nature of 
                        actual movement-forms, actually dynamic formation, 
                        is very much alive. This can lead us to new, richer 
                        formal domains.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>Monday, March 13, exercise:</p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        I: Pasture of the  
                        grazing animal
                        Functions of this part
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        II: Range of the  
                        hunting animal
                        Functions of the other 
                        part
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url="..."/>
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url="..."/>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url="..."/>
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url="..."/>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        III: Possible combination of I and II, leading to 
                        the subordination of one character or to the 
                        equal ranking of the two.
                    </p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="div_Klee_lesson8">
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../number8"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        Monday, March 20, 1922
                    </p>  
                    <p>
                        The function of a visual work is the way in which 
                        the work's construction, set in motion over time,
                        communicates itself to the eye and the way in which 
                        the character of movement inherent in each work is 
                        imposed upon the eye and upon the powers of reception 
                        lying behind it.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Here we touch upon the old story of effect, 
                        but through emphasis on the character of movement 
                        inherent in each visual work, not the effect 
                        generally, the effect per se, but the kind of effect 
                        particular to each case.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        To differentiate these kinds of effects by classi- 
                        fying them amounts to classifying the types of works.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        As we saw last time, every work, even 
                        the most concise, moves within time both as it 
                        emerges (productively) and as it is apprehended 
                        (receptively). Our eye is constructed in such a 
                        way that it scans, over time, all that we perceive 
                        visually.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The eye, wearied of familiar nature or 
                        familiar culture, steers towards new, stimulating 
                        peculiarities. Should it fall to a visual work to 
                        exert such stimuli, then the eye steers towards that 
                        area where, as the greatest force of attraction, 
                        the strongest unfolding of pictorial energy asserts 
                        itself.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Such a stimulus is always of a relative 
                        nature. If, on a white plane√ó that has made the 
                        eye curious, an especially deep black is produced 
                        somewhere, then this black in comparison with that 
                        white is a quite strong energy.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Or when on a green plane enticing closer
                        examination,
                    </p>
                    <p> √ó my sheet of paper on the blackboard</p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        a sharply contrasting red asserts itself, then this 
                        time the red is the special energy. The same applies 
                        to white on black, warm on cool, lively on calm, and 
                        vice versa, higher on lower, stronger on weaker, 
                        harder on softer. Or active on static, and all the 
                        other opposites that, once created, have the power 
                        to wrest the eye towards themselves.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        With the feeling (which was somewhat reinforced 
                        by the last exercise), with the feeling, that the 
                        explanations from last time were not yet clear 
                        enough, and in order to be able to build more 
                        securely on them, I am going to backtrack a little.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        To demonstrate again for you how both the product 
                        and the recept move in time, I will choose as my 
                        product the most concise construct that cannot emerge 
                        at a single stroke (not even one produced with single 
                        strokes from each of two hands at once):  
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig1"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        A construct that consists of the factors "first," 
                        "second," and "third." This product was not created 
                        in a single stroke but rather took its time; nor
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        indeed can it be assimilated in a single moment either, 
                        despite its truly marked concision. Rather: 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The stimulated eye jumps to the strongest energy, 
                        to "first,"
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <graphic url="..."/>
                    </p>
                    <p>compares it with "second"</p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url="..."/>
                        <cb n="right"/>and with "third,"
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="center"/><graphic url="..."/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        (Recept of
                        fig. 1)
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        which again means a succession or a temporal movement. 
                        Here the reception image or, in short, the recept, 
                        presents the function of the product (fig. 1). 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        We now have before us: there (fig. 1), a planar 
                        image as the product and, here, a linear image as the 
                        recept.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Note
                        <graphic url="..."/> There [fig. 1] the planes are to be thought of as 
                        active planes and here [fig. 2] as active lines, which are 
                        not (mind you!) mutually dependent on one another in the way 
                        they were represented earlier, i.e., as here: <graphic url="..."/> where the 
                        passive lines depend on the active plane, or here: <graphic url="..."/> where 
                        the plane, as opposed to the lines, is the result and is 
                        therefore passive. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Therefore: there, active planes and, here, active lines 
                        that are functionally linked with each other.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Closer examination of the reception image reveals a 
                        movement gradually retreating from the base of the 
                        force, or a gradually weaker valuation compared with 
                        the fundamental principal value. Sequential order and 
                        ranking order coincide. 
                    </p> 
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig3"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        These red forms of diminishing force are the expression  
                        of the function of the three values of our production 
                        image (fig. 1). At the same time, the new form is 
                        itself again an image and indeed an image with pure 
                        movement-form.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        We will make this last experience even clearer yet 
                        with a new product.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig4"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        This new product consists of nine graded values that, for sim-  
                        plicity's sake, I represent only with quantitative differences. 
                        Language and function would of course find even more vivid 
                        expression with gradations based on tone value or color value. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For the purpose of configuring the reception, the 
                        centric character of this product leads me to schematize the 
                        gradation of values in the form of nine circles that recede 
                        further and further from the center. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson8_fig5"/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        The diagonals may also be considered.
                        And, with that, the schema in which  
                        the action of reception is to be played  
                        out has been prepared.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Before approaching the product, let us envision the 
                        following little prelude: We have moved about, getting 
                        our exercise for some time in the countryside and are 
                        satisfied and tired after our plein-air impressions, 
                        so that coming back into the dark house feels like a 
                        relief. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The room in which we now find ourselves is 
                        completely black, empty and black. The next room that we 
                        enter is also black with the exception of one painted 
                        wall.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Here our thoroughly stimulated eye now pounces on 
                        the pure white note, which I have labeled "first." Then 
                        to the still very light note labeled "second," and next 
                        it proceeds to the remaining values, in increasingly 
                        darker gradations.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig6"/>
                    </figure> 
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Thus, the path via the separate stimulus-points arranges 
                        itself in the form of a spiral around the white in the 
                        center. The stimulus-points recede ever further from the 
                        center, while maintaining their relatedness to it.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig7"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        The product (fig. 4) consisted of solemnly stable and 
                        quiescent forms. Its recept, the function of this stably 
                        formed construct, is the purest movement-form conceivable, a 
                        spiral. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        And so, with every further attempt to represent the 
                        functions of a visual work, we will obtain movement-forms 
                        again and again; the further we advance towards the essence 
                        of the function, the purer the movement-forms.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig8"/>
                    </figure> 
                    <p>
                        This new product shows, in contrast to before, a now 
                        more erratic arrangement of the values. The preceding 
                        pastorale of the grazing cattle has become the range of 
                        the hunting predator, as will be clearly shown in the 
                        corresponding form of the function.
                    </p>
                    <p> 
                        As the first schema to represent this function, to start 
                        with I choose a more epic system (to be read from left 
                        to right) and note on it the values corresponding to the 
                        leaps in value in the product, not in order of rank, but 
                        from bottom to top in the sequence third, fourth, eighth, 
                        ninth, First, fifth, seventh, sixth, second, in which the 
                        particular position of the One at middle height should be 
                        kept in mind. Ranking order and sequential order are not 
                        identical.                    
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson8_fig9"/>
                        <cb n="center"/>
                        For the second schema, I 
                        choose one that is more 
                        dramatic, with high values 
                        in the middle, therefore 
                        one organized centrally, 
                        and I group values in the 
                        product according to their 
                        proximity to the center: 
                        first (center), eighth, 
                        fifth, ninth, fourth, 
                        seventh, sixth, third, and 
                        second
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url=".../lesson8_fig10"/>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In both schemata, I put the notes in the places that correspond 
                        to the positions of values in the product, and, by connecting 
                        according to rank, I obtain two different recepts that 
                        naturally resemble each other internally to a hair. 
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig11"/>
                    </figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig12"/>
                    </figure> 
                    <p>
                        Having arrived at the dynamic form, we first 
                        want to make a slight distinction.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The movement of a formal element that leads to the 
                        creation of a new formal element need not also produce 
                        a dynamic form. The movement of a point into the mathe
                        matical straight line <graphic url="..."/> is
                        indeed a movement-action but not a movement-form. This 
                        same line, if it is then pushed to produce a plane, is 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url="..."/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        not a dynamic line because it 
                        is no longer a line at all but 
                        a plane. However, even the
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        plane thus generated (through the line's movement-action) 
                        still need not present a dynamic character as a plane.
                        A visible state of dynamism first arises from gradual 
                        growth or diminution with regard to the quantity or 
                        quality of the energy applied.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        You will recall the role of the weighing scales,N
                        when we were still stable and static and were weighing 
                        the values against each other on either side. What are the 
                        scales to us now in the measurement of dynamic values? 
                        How shall we weigh things that don't keep still?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        But perhaps the following bit of imagining has something 
                        calming in itself:
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig13"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        This little building is supposed to stand on very small 
                        feet! That won't be very easy. So get the scales over 
                        here, and make that the gold-weighing scales. The weights 
                        tally up: 4 + 1 = 2 + 3. But in practice the thing still 
                        looks rather dubious.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        What to do? Let us empathize with it--we who, after 
                        all, are ourselves buildings standing on small feet 
                        and who must not fall down. What do we do in order 
                        not to fall? What do we do when we have not succeeded 
                        in establishing the calm of stasis through a counter
                        balancing shift (on a small scale) of our weighted parts?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        First we move a leg (enlargement of the base) and 
                        perhaps the other soon afterwards. And finally we walk; 
                        that makes balancing easier.
                    </p>
                <pb/>
                    <p>We have become a dynamic form and sense relief.</p>
                    <p>
                        And our little building on a small foot? It can't 
                        walk, can it?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        It can't walk but perhaps another kind of movement 
                        suits it.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Let's not enlarge its base but, instead, let us 
                        place it on a point and set it swinging vigorously in 
                        motion about itself.  
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig14"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Then it's called a top, the top that every child knows 
                        does not fall as long as the motion lasts, as long as 
                        the top spins. Just as calming for us can be a rolling 
                        wheel, the boy's hoop, or even the spinning diabolo, 
                        which understands the art of dancing on the high wire.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson8_fig15"/>
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url=".../lesson8_fig16"/>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        With in principle such calming thoughts,  we will keep 
                        looking for a replacement for the now  "obsolete" 
                        weighing scales. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The pendulum is a very ingenious   little instrument 
                        consisting of a small lead weight, w, and a line, 
                        which swings back and forth from a fixed point, p, 
                        the center; the line, as radius, moves with the weight.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        The concept of back and forth is essential here, 
                        i.e., the property of the pendulum that consists in 
                        immediately describing the corresponding counter
                        motion to each motion.
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/> <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig17a"/> 
                        <cb n="center"/> <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig17b"/>
                        <cb n="right"/> <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig17c"/>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This one case of the compensatory unification of 
                        motion and counter-motion is, however, not the only 
                        possibility. We can think of a less machine-like 
                        handling, even a very sensitive manual one. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Let us take a very long line √ó and guide the weight with 
                        appreciable slackness.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        Handled this way, 
                        the lead describes 
                        both motion and 
                        counter-motion 
                        independently.
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url=".../lesson8_fig18"/>
                    </p>
                    <p>√ó one of M√©lisande's hairs</p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        We can proceed yet further from the slackened manual 
                        handling to the sentimental journey of the central 
                        point, p, and the pendulum-script will become the 
                        transcribed expression of the particular form of that 
                        journey.  
                    </p> 
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig19"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Here, for example, the pendulum-script is the dynamic 
                        expression of the vertical straight line, and we arrive 
                        at a dynamic variation on the static construction.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Furthermore, we could guide the straight form of 
                        the journey dynamically, along a meandering path, or we 
                        could wander in any form we like.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Or we could complete the slackening of the line 
                        at the right moment by letting it go, and the pendulum 
                        becomes a gentle sling, writing in this way, and, like 
                        the counter-motions of the fixed pendulum, the slingshot 
                        counter-motion is easy to understand and complete.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        However, a new phenomenon occurs if, once more allowing 
                        the pendulum to swing quite calmly to and fro, we think 
                        of the force of gravity being abolished suddenly in the 
                        middle of an oscillation (fig. 20), or if we lend the 
                        swing so much force that gravity is defeated.   
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                        In this way, with the pendulum no longer bound to the 
                        earth, the cosmic movement-form suddenly arises:
                    </p>
                    <p>The pendulum swings around in a circle.</p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig20"/>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        In this closed, endless motion the need for a counter
                        motion ceases, and indeed the pendulum renounces the 
                        counter-motion in the new circumstances. 
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url=".../lesson8_fig21"/>
                    </figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        As opposed to the previous force, which I called 
                        the force of gravity, we now become acquainted with a 
                        new force that I call centrifugal force.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        New journeys are conceivable with the circling 
                        pendulum, too, if the center is set in motion or 
                        if movement starts with the radius being either 
                        lengthened, upon which ever wider circles sweep out, or 
                        shortened, upon which the circles grow ever tighter, 
                        until the lovely spectacle dies with a jerk, in the 
                        point.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><graphic url=".../lesson8_fig22"/>
                        <cb n="right"/><graphic url=".../lesson8_fig22a"/>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The latter is the story of the spiral. Its movement 
                        is no longer endless, inherently quiescent, and so 
                        the question of direction of motion is raised. We must 
                        know this direction because the question dependent on 
                        the lengthening or shortening of the radius (fig. 22a) 
                        is essentially psychic. It runs: Do I loosen myself 
                        from the center in ever freer movement? Or will my
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        movements become more and more bound to a center until 
                        it finally swallows me whole?
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>either <graphic url="..."/>
                        <cb n="center"/><graphic url="..."/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        motion of the radius 
                        away from C   
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>or<graphic url="..."/>
                        <cb n="center"/><graphic url="..."/>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        motion of the
                        radius towards C
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This is nothing less than the question of life and 
                        death. And the little arrow makes the decision.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>Monday, March 27, 1922</p> 
                    <p>
                        Movement exercise: "The Fountain," not the appearance 
                        of the fountain but the essence of the fountain, the 
                        forces of the water as arrangement and above all as 
                        dynamic functioning. 
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url="..."/>
                    </figure>
